"HD6350","HD6351","HD6352"]}],"tags":["indian_wars","spanish_american_war"],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"military","header":"First in French, far from it in drawing","body":"At West Point he stood first in French and Spanish “without having to work very hard” and was far from distinguished in drawing, his classmate Dorst remembered. Five frontier years with the 4th Cavalry followed — scouting from Fort Clark’s armed camps, where no one walked two hundred yards unarmed."},{"number":2,"category":"military","header":"Snow-blind on Mackenzie’s winter expedition","body":"A volunteer on Crook’s Powder River Expedition after the Custer disaster, he rode in Mackenzie’s November 1876 destruction of the Cheyenne village — and left on sick leave, his eyes burned by glare off the snow. He resigned in 1878, “regretted, loved and respected.”"},{"number":3,"category":"business","header":"Seven thousand acres of American tea","body":"Commanding the 3rd Connecticut Volunteers in South Carolina in 1898, the colonel saw commercial promise in southern tea and bought four Colleton County plantations — Holly Grove, Rutledge Island, Mowbray, Turkey Hill — whose flourishing gardens and factory his son Frederick managed."},{"number":4,"category":"legacy","header":"The Russian ambassador took his house","body":"The stately residence he built at 1634 I Street, facing Farragut Square in Washington, later housed the Russian ambassador. He was president of New London’s Pequot Casino Association at his death, a clubman to the last afternoon."},{"number":5,"category":"family","header":"Born on his brother’s thirteenth birthday","body":"May 2, 1851 — thirteen years to the day after his brother Edmund, born May 2, 1838. The Tyler brothers shared a birthday a generation apart."}],"sources":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[{"type":"family_orbit","related_id":"X03329","display_label":"was the patent-medicine magnate father of his w